 with <i>coffer</i>, and it may be that <i>Cofin</i> was used to denote a keeper of the (royal) coffer, attested in Anglo-Latin <i>cofferarius</i>. Compare   Coffer  . The modern English word <i>coffin</i> is a specialized development of this term, not attested until the 16th century.","History: Tristram Coffin came from Brixham, Devon, to Haverhill, MA, before 1647. An important line of his descendants is associated with Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Coffer","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>cofre</i>, <i>coffre</i>, <i>coffer</i> ‘box, chest’ (from Old French <i>cof(f)rehere</i>), used to denote a box or coffer maker (Old French <i>coffrier</i>), perhaps also for a treasurer.","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Kaufer   or <b>Kauffer</b>."]},{"name":"Coffing","meanings":["English: variant of   Coffin  ."]}]},{"name":"Roesia","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A baptismal name derived, like the surname Rous, Rouse, Rowse, from Old French rous, red; from Latin rufus."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowse","meanings":["A baptismal name derived, like the surname Rous, Rouse, Rowse, from Old French rous, red; from Latin rufus."]},{"name":"Roese","meanings":["A baptismal name derived, like the surname Rous, Rouse, Rowse, from Old French rous, red; from Latin rufus."]},{"name":"Rous","meanings":["A baptismal name derived, like the surname Rous, Rouse, Rowse, from Old French rous, red; from Latin rufus."]},{"name":"Rouse","meanings":["A baptismal name derived, like the surname Rous, Rouse, Rowse, from Old French rous, red; from Latin rufus."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":2,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":37,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","de